{"cursor":"12787","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n'Miller indices' form a notation system in crystallography for planes in crystal\n(Bravais) lattices.\n\nIn particular, a family of lattice planes is determined by three integers h, k,\nand â, the Miller indices. They are written (hkâ), and each index denotes a\nplane orthogonal to a direction in the basis of the reciprocal lattice vectors.\nBy convention, negative integers are written with a bar, as in for â3. The\nintegers are usually written in lowest terms, i.e. their greatest common divisor\nshould be 1. Miller index 100 represents a plane orthogonal to\ndirection h; index 010 represents a plane orthogonal to direction k,\nand index 001 represents a plane orthogonal to â.\n\nThere are also several related notations: Neil W. Ashcroft and N.\nDavid Mermin, Solid State Physics (Harcourt: New York, 1976) *the notation\n{hkâ} denotes the set of all planes that are equivalent to (hkâ) by the symmetry\nof the lattice. In the context of crystal directions (not planes), the\ncorresponding notations are: *[hkâ], with square instead of round brackets,\ndenotes a direction in the basis of the direct lattice vectors instead of the\nreciprocal lattice; and *similarly, the notation \\left\\langle\nhk\\ell\\right\\rangle denotes the set of all directions that are equivalent\nto [hkâ] by symmetry.\n\nMiller indices were introduced in 1839 by the British mineralogist William\nHallowes Miller. The method was also historically known as the Millerian system,\nand the indices as Millerian, [http://dictionary.oed.com Oxford English\nDictionary Online] (Consulted May 2007) although this is now rare.\n\nThe Miller indices are defined with respect to any choice of unit cell and not\nonly with respect to primitive basis vectors, as is sometimes stated.\n","linknr":203,"url":"Miller_index","recorded":1374544679,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Miller_index&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Miller_index&act